PCA

  1. Use Breast Cancer Wisconsin data set from the UCI Machine learning repo to plot the PCA analysis. Use the prcomp function runs PCA on the data.

  1. You want to explain difference between malignant and benign tumors using Visualisation and add the response variable (diagnosis) to the plot

  2. Construct some kind of model using the first 6 principal components to predict whether a tumor is benign or malignant and then compare it to a model using the original 30 variables.

plot(cumpro[0:15], xlab = "PC #", ylab = "Amount of explained variance", main = "Cumulative variance plot")

plot(data_pca$x[,1],data_pca$x[,2], xlab="PC1 (44.3%)", ylab = "PC2 (19%)", main = "PC1 / PC2 - plot")

pca_br_cancer <- data.frame(
  pc1 = data_pca$x[,1],
  pc2 = data_pca$x[,2],
  diagnosis = data$diagnosis
